PROFILES.
~~~~~~~~~
Profiles define requirements for diagnostics. They have names to help
you remember what they are for. You "attach" profiles to the
diagnostics to define how you want the diagnostics. One diagnostic can
have more than one set of profiles attached to it. In this case the
diagnostic needs to be CLONED and alternative profiles attached to the
clone.  All chosen diagnostics must have all three types of profiles
attached.

TIME PROFILES.
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
Define temporal processing requirements and output requirements. Examples are
time means and accumulations.
Some diagnostics are not available every timestep and can only have time
profiles attached that reflect this.
See the help windows in the time profiles.

DOMAIN PROFILES.
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
Define spatial processing requirements as well as the output domain (sub areas
and levels). Examples of spatial processing are vertical and full field means.
STASH cannot change the vertical coordinate type of a diagnostic (or the
pseudo level type). Hence the right profiles must be used with the right
diagnostics.
See the help windows in the domain profiles.

USAGE PROFILES.
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
Usage profiles define the "output" destination of the diagnostics to which
they are attached.
Diagnostics can be written to:
	PPfile output streams: for later analysis.
	Mean PP files:         for later analysis.
	Internal space:   for use in other parts of the UM (such as coupling).
Particular care needs to be taken with climate mean diagnostics.	
See the help windows in the usage profiles.


